Content:"WASHINGTON  —   The support was in short supply at a key moment for a man who called President Barack Obama’s policies “a total disaster? and whose campaign slogan was “Make America great again. ? A coalition of    Republican businessmen and women poured out that message in a letter on Sunday, urging Mr. Trump to reject the possibility of   connections with Russia and to support legislation to support a special prosecutor to investigate Russia’s interference in the election and the possibility of collusion between the Trump campaign and Russia. “These people’s response to this was immediate and passionate,? said Mary Pat Bonin, a spokeswoman for the Knights of St. John, an American Legion affiliate that once led a rally in New York for a president who embraced the    Trump brand. “The president has changed his position on Russia, and I believe people in charge of his campaign immediately took the wrong position,? Ms. Bonin added. Senator Chris Murphy, Democrat of Connecticut, also on the letter, said that nothing like this had ever happened and asked Mr. Trump to return to his normal position. “If anything, this looks like the beginning of an   cascade of events, but if it were anything but, who knows where this would have gone?? Mr. Murphy said on MSNBC’s “Morning Joe? program. “I believe a direct link between the campaign and Russia is still possible, but if it was anything but anything except a direct link, then there is now a kind of cascade effect. ? Several Republican senators said the same thing. “When the president calls for loyalty to the president, then we should get along,? said Senator Chuck Grassley, Republican of Iowa and the chairman of the Judiciary Committee. “That’s what it will come down to, do we need to do anything else on Russia to get past this??"<endoftext|>
